**Security artifacts:**

**Scope and assets**

*   **Primary assets:** Customer Profile, account balances, transaction history, credentials, cheque data, bill pay schedules, overdraft settings.
*   **Secondary assets:** Audit logs, configuration (interest rates, limits), reconciliation reports, session tokens.
*   **Actors:** Customers, bankers (ops), administrators, external billers, attackers (external), malicious insiders.

**Trust boundaries**

*   **Client ‚Üî Web server:** Browser to IIS over TLS.
*   **Web server ‚Üî App services:** ASP.NET application to database, payment gateways, mail/SMS services.
*   **Banker portal:** Elevated access with stricter controls and network segmentation.
*   **Batch jobs:** Overnight interest/overdraft calculations and reconciliation.

**Authentication and Login:**

*   **User Registration**
    *   Collect only necessary details (name, email, phone, account type).
    *   Validate inputs server-side (never trust client-side validation alone).
    *   Store passwords using **hashing with salt** (e.g., PBKDF2, bcrypt).
    *   Send activation link or banker approval before enabling login.
*   **Login**
    *   Username + password as primary login.
    *   Add **optional OTP (SMS/email)** for sensitive actions (bill payments, transfers).
    *   After **3 failed attempts ‚Üí lock account**. Unlock only by banker/admin.
*   **Password Rules**
    *   Minimum 8‚Äì10 characters, mix of letters, numbers, symbols.
    *   Prevent reuse of last 3 passwords.
    *   Provide ‚ÄúForgot Password‚Äù with secure reset link (expires in 15 minutes).

**Session Management:**

*   **Session Tokens**
    *   Use ASP.NET built-in session cookies.
    *   Mark cookies as Secure (HTTPS only) and HttpOnly (not accessible via JavaScript).
    *   Set SameSite=Strict to prevent CSRF attacks.
*   **Session Timeout**
    *   Auto logout after **15 minutes of inactivity**.
    *   Absolute session expiry after **8 hours** (even if active).
*   **Session Renewal**
    *   Regenerate session ID after login and after privilege changes (e.g., banker approval).
    *   Invalidate old session immediately on logout.
*   **Concurrent Sessions**
    *   Allow only **one active session per user** (optional for stricter security).
    *   Notify user if login happens from a new device/location.

**Authorization and roles**

**Role-based access control (RBAC)**

| Role | Key permissions | Constraints |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Customer | View balances/statements; deposit cheques; pay bills; transfer money; view statuses | Only own resources; daily withdrawal/transfer limits; step-up MFA for high-value |
| Banker | Approve registrations; process cheques; change cheque statuses; unlock accounts; run reconciliation | Dual control for fines/bounces; workflow approvals; elevated logging |
| Admin | Manage configurations (interest rates, limits); manage roles; view system health | Dual control; change management; signed config; limited to admin network |
| Auditor | Read-only access to logs, reports, configurations | No data modification; immutable log access |

**Implementation notes**

*   **Policy-based authorization:** ASP.NET Core- IAuthorizationService with custom requirements (e.g. HighValueTransactionPolicy).
*   **Resource scoping:** Use opaque identifiers; enforce ownership checks server-side; avoid client-supplied IDs.
*   **Dual control:** Require two distinct banker/admin approvals for sensitive actions (bounce fines, config changes).
*   **Least privilege:** Separate service accounts for batch jobs, DB access; deny-by-default.
